.TH ws_validate_config 8 "May 2026" "SYSTEM ADMINISTRATION COMMANDS"

.SH NAME
ws_validate_config \- validate workspace configuration files

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ws_validate_config
[\-h] [\-\-config CONFIGFILE] [CONFIGFILE]

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ws_validate_config
is a validation tool for workspace configuration files. It reads the
configuration from the specified file or from the default locations
(\fI/etc/ws.d\fR, \fI/etc/ws.conf\fR) and validates all required settings.

The tool checks for:
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
Presence of required configuration clauses
.IP \(bu 4
Correctness of workspace definitions
.IP \(bu 4
Existence of configured directories
.IP \(bu 4
Correct permissions on spaces, database and deleted directories
.IP \(bu 4
Correct ownership (uid/gid) matching dbuid/dbgid settings
.RE

.B Note:
This tool only validates the configuration file structure and configuration
values. It does not validate database contents or filesystem contents.

.PP

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\-h, \-\-help
display usage help text
.TP
\-\-config CONFIGFILE
path to config file. Only effective for root or when running in user mode.
.TP
CONFIGFILE
alternative way to specify config file path as positional argument.

.SH VALIDATION CHECKS
The tool performs the following validation checks:

.SS Global Configuration
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
Check clustername is defined
.IP \(bu 4
Check admins list is not empty
.IP \(bu 4
Check adminmail list is not empty
.IP \(bu 4
Check default workspace is defined and exists in filesystems list
.IP \(bu 4
Check maxduration, durationdefault, reminderdefault, maxextensions values
.IP \(bu 4
Validate dbuid and dbgid are set
.RE

.SS Filesystem Configuration (for each filesystem)
.RS
.IP \(bu 4
Check filesystem name is defined
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces directory list is not empty
.IP \(bu 4
Check deleted path is defined for each space
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces directories exist (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces/deleted directories exist (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces permissions are 0755 (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces/deleted permissions are 0755 (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces ownership matches dbuid:dbgid (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check spaces/deleted ownership matches dbuid:dbgid (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database path is defined
.IP \(bu 4
Check database directory exists (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database/.ws_db_magic exists (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database/deleted directory exists (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database permissions are 0755 (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database/.ws_db_magic permissions are 0644 (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database/deleted permissions are 0755 (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database ownership matches dbuid:dbgid (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database/.ws_db_magic ownership matches dbuid:dbgid (warning if not)
.IP \(bu 4
Check database/deleted ownership matches dbuid:dbgid (warning if not)
.RE

.SS Warnings vs Errors
All directory existence checks, permission checks, and ownership checks
emit warnings but allow validation to continue. Only missing required
configuration clauses (like clustername, admins, default workspace, etc.)
are treated as errors and cause the tool to exit with code 1.

.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
validate default config files:
.B ws_validate_config
.TP
validate specific config file:
.B ws_validate_config /etc/ws.d/custom.conf
.TP
validate with explicit option:
.B ws_validate_config --config /etc/ws.d/custom.conf

.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
0
Configuration is valid
.TP
1
Configuration is invalid or contains errors

.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/ws.d
default directory for configuration files
.TP
.I /etc/ws.conf
default configuration file (used if /etc/ws.d does not exist)

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ws (7),
.BR ws_expirer (8),
.BR ws_editdb (8),
.BR ws_allocate (1)

